english:
  title: On the Origins of Flood and Drought
  author: Lee Gok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Are floods and droughts truly the work of Heaven's decree, or the consequence of human effort? Even the sage-kings Yao and Tang could not escape them—so we call it Heaven's decree. Yet omens and portents bear witness to human action. The ancients cultivated human effort to respond to Heaven's decree, and thus endured calamities lasting seven or nine years without their people suffering ruin. Later generations, surrendering to Heaven's decree while abandoning human effort, see their people fall into ditches and ravines after but one or two years of disaster.

    Our state not only surveys the harvest each season, but stores provisions month by month, day by day. Can we not say human effort is being cultivated? And yet since last year's waters and drought, the people have suffered greatly. Many remedies have been attempted, yet we fail to grasp the root cause. Why?

    I once heard the elders say: moving people and grain, feeding the hungry and giving drink to the thirsty—these merely ease the urgent crisis before us. But if we wish to prevent future calamities based on what has already come to pass, should we not examine the very source?

    The people entrust their lives to their magistrates. When harm or benefit befalls them, they appeal to these officials as children appeal to parents. Should not parents cast aside harm for their children without thought of personal gain? Yet today's magistrates are not thus. When two men dispute in court, should one possess silver, the other's case becomes groundless. How can such people not die in resentment? How can their wounded spirits not disturb the harmony of heaven and earth? This is what summons flood and drought.

    Inspectors oversee magistrates—we call them Provincial Inspectors. They should investigate corruption and integrity, rewarding the honest and punishing the corrupt. But today this does not happen. Inspectors-General oversee the Provincial Inspectors, examining their competence and removing or promoting accordingly. Yet this too has ceased.

    Occasionally one finds someone devoted to ancient ways, yet such persons find no place in our time. For today's Provincial Inspectors have become yesterday's Inspectors-General, today's Inspectors-General have become yesterday's magistrates, and all support and shield one another. Thus things have fallen into disorder.

    Should our people once witness magistrates as they were in ancient times, should today's magistrates once witness Provincial Inspectors as they were of old, should today's Provincial Inspectors once witness Inspectors-General as they were of old—then our common folk might yet be spared the pit and ravine.

    So whether we speak of Heaven's decree or human effort, the crux is this alone: rid ourselves of corruption. And if we would rid ourselves of corruption, the laws and institutions already exist, complete and ready. We need only implement them. This depends solely upon he who governs all under Heaven.
  footnotes:
    - Yao and Tang were legendary sage-kings of ancient China, exemplars of virtuous rulership.
    - The reference to 'seven or nine years' versus 'one or two years' illustrates how the ancients' moral governance sustained the people through prolonged hardship, while later neglect of virtue caused swift collapse.
    - The hierarchy of officials—magistrates, Provincial Inspectors, and Inspectors-General—represents the oversight system meant to maintain integrity throughout government. Lee Gok critiques how this system had become corrupted by mutual protection rather than accountability.
